The paper deals with scalable and secure computation in a network setting, which suggests that it could belong to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) category. The paper also discusses Byzantine agreement and leader election, which are topics related to cryptography and security, indicating that it could also belong to the Cryptography and Security (cs.CR) category. The use of randomization and analysis of communication costs suggest that it could belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) category. The paper also discusses information theory and communication complexity, which are topics related to Information Theory (cs.IT) and Learning (cs.LG) categories.
